  "format": "Sean Fennessey talks to Ike Barinholtz about writing, directing, and starring in The Oath, a Thanksgiving-dinner-goes-dystopian comedy he shot in 19 days, plus the state of studio comedy.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Ike Barinholtz on 'The Oath'",
      "guest": "Ike Barinholtz on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Oath",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "Barinholtz's writing-directing-starring debut, shot in 19 days for QC Entertainment (Get Out). Started as a real argument at his family's Thanksgiving table after Trump's election and merged with an idea about a government loyalty pledge that comes with tax and healthcare perks. Tiffany Haddish's character is loosely based on his own wife; John Cho plays a civil-servant enforcer; Billy Magnussen's villain was rewritten as a young man after Charlottesville. The frame tightens and the palette darkens as the movie turns from family comedy to something closer to home invasion."
        },
        {
          "title": "Children of Men",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "His go-to dystopia touchstone and a direct model for The Oath, though not for the jokes: there are none, save Michael Caine's fart. He drew from its sense of people clinging to a decayed world."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mrs. Miniver",
          "year": 1942,
          "note": "The Greer Garson drama he thought of as two movies stitched together: idyllic English countryside life, then a Nazi soldier shows up in the house."
        },
        {
          "title": "M*A*S*H",
          "year": 1970,
          "note": "Cited for Altman's ability to land a genuine joke inside carnage: the blood-soaked surgeons batting away Hot Lips' small talk."
        },
        {
          "title": "Manchester by the Sea",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "His example of a scene playing agony and comedy at once: the gurney that won't fit in the ambulance."
        }
      ]
    }
